@NODE What_is_EasInt? "What is EasInt?"

            EasInt is a program dedicated exclusively to the  AMOS
            PROFESSIONAL programmers.

            Many of them have certainly appreciated the functional
            AMOS PRO built-in Interface Language and its  capacity
            of dealing with buttons, sliders, etc.
            Maybe someone has found it  quite difficult  to learn,
            and certainly many don't find pleasant at all to build
            interfaces with such a strange language.

            Like them,I couldn't stand the idea of typing odd com-
            mands like BI, BA, BU, SI, SA, SM......., so I thought
            that a Point 'n'Click Interface Editor was what anyone
            using Inteface Language needed.

            That's why I have written this Editor, which allows us
            to program our Panels with ease.
            Now, we no longer need to write a lot of long strings,
            this program will do it for us!

            If you don't believe me, just think that EasInt reque-
            sters have been (partly) written using the program it-
            self!!!

            Even if it makes easy to build  Panels, you still need
            to know how to call and handle 'em in the program they
            written for (obviously I can't know what ya want to do
            with your interfaces panels!!!).

@ENDNODE

@NODE Install "How to install and run it?"

            HARD DRIVE INSTALLATION
            =======================

            The program can be installed anywhere on the HD with-
            out any special procedure (just copy it).The required
            data are _already_ saved with the code.  Yet, in case
            they are not available (this only happens if you save
            EasInt WITHOUT its  Resource Bank  or delete it using
            the command "Erase Bk#" - I advise you not to do it),
            the program  will try to load 1 of the supplied files
            (@{"RESOURCES/EasInt_res.abk" Link Stuff}) from the current dir.
            Note that  if the program is invoked  as an accessory
            (from the "Accessories" Menu)and the Resource Bank is
            NOT loaded, the program will not work, as the AMOS E-
            ditor doesn't keep track of the resources used by the
            accessories.

            RUNNING THE PROGRAM
            ===================

            EasInt can be launched either from an AMOS PRO Editor
            window or as an ACCESSORY:  I recommend you to run it
            in this way, so  that you can  take advantage  of two
            great features: @{"'Import from AMOS' & 'Send to AMOS'" Link Communicating_with_Editor}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Foreword "IMPORTANT FOREWORD"

            ************************************************
            * IMPORTANT!!!!! - please read it thoroughly   *
            ************************************************

            Sigh. This foreword is as much important as SAD.

            But let's (possibly) proceed with calm and peace
            of mind. Please, be patient while reading it, as
            there are some very important things. I apologi-
            ze  for the  lengthy bunch of words spent on the
            aspects not strictly necessary:  I just COULDN'T
            avoid to write them.

            I started this program ~2 years ago,  when I was
            still playing around with AMOS (now my fave lan-
            guage is asm - this DOESN'T mean I no longer li-
            ke AMOS) and had my first contacts with 1 of its
            sub-languages:  the interface language.  I found 
            it quite interesting and,after a brief period of
            practice, also very effective.  Yet, there was a
            thing I couldn't absolutely put up with: the we-
            ird code. Since the beginning I felt the need of
            an editor,  which probably  didn't exsist due to
            the  difficulty and  relatively low-interest the
            interface sub-langugage would arouse in the AMOS
            programmers (at least IMHO ).  The only solution
            was to program it by myself.  After some days of
            intense programming,  the prog began to grow and
            shape interestingly.... at a certain point I was
            even able to use it to build its own requesters!
            Many other programming  hours elapsed and I rea-
            lized  that it was the editor  AMOS  was missing
            (forgive me this lack of modesty, please). "What
            if I send it to Europress for evaluation?!?" - I
            thought,  nourishing a strong hope in a warm re-
            sponse. A month later (snail-mail's fault) I got
            the answer, and it more or less said: " Yeah, it
            seems good, but our technicians couldn't test it
            to its full potential since it's incomplete...".
            The reply was kind and they also returned me the
            floppy I sent. But, NO. It *DID* hurt me.  I had
            the clear sensation (and I still believe so)that 
            the number of "technicians" who  tested the prog
            was equal to _zero_.  Maybe ( I hope that ) this
            is not the truth, and I tried to convince myself
            of this. But while the reason says one thing,the
            "heart" can tell exactly the opposite.  I didn't
            long to keep programming it,  so I stopped deve-
            loping just when I had almost finished to prepa-
            re the most important routines:  the ones desti-
            ned to produce the code for buttons. This is the
            state  which you find  this prog in.  Yes, it is
            *INCOMPLETE* (though 75-85% of its functions are
            completely implemented)and also @{"*BUGGY*" Link BUGS}.You can
            blame/flame me for this,  just let me add that I
            decided to release it because it had NO sense to
            keep it forgotten somewhere  in my HD.  In fact,
            I found it while reorganizing dirs & files. "Oh,
            look, that old prog..... let's see what I did so
            much time ago..." - I ran it. Since then, only 1
            thought in my mind: " Hey!! but this can be use-
            ful...". Hence the release. Now, let me tell you
            the reasons  why I can't fix and/or complete it:

            ° I clearly remember that the code is messy  and
              also that I had decided to modify _vastly_ its
              main structure to offer a more solid base  for
              the old and, above all, the new ( the ones not
              implemented) critic functions.  Doing this now
              is impossible:  I could only  re-write it from
              the scratch, supposing I had enough free time.

            ° It's a loooong time  I don't program with AMOS
              and  I almost completely  forgot the interface
              language: it would take me some hrs of intense
              practice to master it again,in order to produ-
              ce good (if not optimal) routines.

            ° As I said above, I'm in constant lack of spare
              time:  the uni studies and all that living far
              from home involves  don't give me much time to
              "resurrect" such an old project.

            ° How many AMOS programmers would use it anyway?
              Few, I guess.

            ° By restarting this project,  I would be forced
              to abandon the other (and more interesting, to
              be honest) projects  I'm carrying on in  those
              short periods of free time.

            ° Such an effort would ask for a (deserved,  you
              should agree) compensation.  To the point: the
              target of this program => low sales.

            I think I made the right move with this release.
            Though,if among you there is a corageous guy who
            wants to improve, complete, fix my program, he's
            welcome!!!I would be glad to receive better ver-
            sions, and there'll be no prob  if he decides to
            to spread it: the only thing he'll have to do is
            to @{"ask me" Link Author} and then distribute it for FREE.

            I am aware that releasing a buggy and incomplete
            prog is lame,  but I just hope you'll understand
            that I can do nothing else.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Features "Features"

            A small guide to the many EasInt's features :

            they are activated through @{" pull-down menus " Link Pull-Down_Menu}
            and many @{" requesters " Link Requesters} which will pop up from
            time to time, depending on the action decided
            by the user.

            The @{"many menu options" Link Main_Options} give you the chance to
            create interfaces  in a way you wouldn't have
            ever dreamt.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Pull-Down_Menu "Pull-Down Menus"

            From a pull-down menu you can call all the functi-
            ons available, which will call their corresponding
            @{" requester(s) " Link Requesters}.

            This menu is always active,except when a requester
            is being displayed.

            If you (like me)  don't like pressing millions and
            millions of times the RMB to summon the menus, you
            will find very comfortable the @{"shortcuts" Link MinorFlaws} assigned
            to almost every menu function.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Requesters "Requesters"

            @{" EasInt graphix " Link Stuff} have been designed to match the
            AMOS PRO style,  thus reaching a good integration
            with the programming environment. I hope you will
            like them ( to say the truth, I just modified the
            standard resources gfx ): I believe they are suf-
            ficiently clear and eye-pleasant.

            The requesters, based on such gfx, should be very
            functional and intuitive.

            By pressing their buttons, typing in their editing
            zones and scrolling their sliders you'll quickly
            create the Panel you need.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Main_Options "Main Options"

            Here is brief description of the most important
            menu options. Many functions are not described
            as they really don't need any explanation.
            For more information call the @{" on-line help " Link HELP}
            directly from the program.

                 @{"  How to create a brand-new  Panel  " Link How_to_create_a_brand-new_Panel}
                 @{"        Can I save my Panel?        " Link Can_I_save_my_Panel?}
                 @{"     Grabbing the Interface Code    " Link Grabbing}
                 @{" Using the Panels  in your programs " Link Using_the_Panels_in_your_programs}
                 @{" Communicating with the AMOS Editor " Link Communicating_with_Editor}
                 @{"          Testing your Panel        " Link Testing_your_Panel}
                 @{"      Editing your Panel by hand    " Link Editing_your_Panel}
@ENDNODE

@NODE How_to_create_a_brand-new_Panel "How to create a brand-new Panel"

            If you want to make a new Panel, the first thing
            you have to do is to choose whether it makes use
            of some Resources or not.

            If it doesn't require a Resource Bank, firstly
            you need to open the screen on which your Panel
            will be displayed;to do this select the Design/
            Screen/Open menu item.
            Once you have opened your screen, you can start
            "programming"your Panel using the other options.

            In the case you want to use some Resources, you
            don not need to open a screen:  just select the
            Design/Resources/Load item. A  new screen  will
            be opened and adapted to the Resources require-
            ments.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Can_I_save_my_Panel? "Can I save my Panel?"

            No.
            Hehehehe!!! Just kidding!!!
            You can, of course.
            With Panel/Save[Save As] your Panel will be sa-
            ved in a file of your choice (in ASCII format).
            Yet, DO NOT modify it with any  text editor, as
            it could be easily refused by the program.

            To load them go to Panel/Load.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Grabbing "Grabbing Interface Code"

            YEAH!!! EasInt can also edit any interface code
            written "by hand" or in any other way.
            In fact we can:

            ° import the code from an ASCII file *NOT* pro-
              produced by EasInt
            ° rip it from an AMOS source, through an exten-
              ded use of the @{"AMOS PRO Editor" Link Communicating_with_Editor}

            As regards to the first option, I must say that
            it has been implemented _before_ the other one,
            so now it is quite useless.
            However, if you have any reason to use this me-
            thod, be prepared to respect a few rules to ma-
            ke EasInt accept your file.  Call the @{"help" Link HELP} for
            more info about the file format  or have a look
            at one of the @{"example files" Link Stuff}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Using_the_Panels_in_your_programs "Using the Panels in your programs"

            You can merge the code produced by EasInt in your
            programs in two ways:

            ° by @{"sending the code directly to the AMOS Editor" Link Communicating_with_Editor}
            ° by inserting the file in which the Panel is sto-
              red in the source code of your AMOS program

            The  last operation can  be done  by selecting the
            "Merge" item of the AMOS Editor menu and  then de-
            leting some lines,exclusively needed by EasInt.
            Leave only  the double-quoted strings and  remeber
            to memorize them into a variable, ex.:

            "BA10,10;SI20,10;..." --->
                                 ---> A$="BA10,10;SI20,10;..."

            "BU1,0,0,8,8,0,0,1;[][]" --->
                           ---> A$=A$+"BU1,0,0,8,8,0,0,1;[][]"

            I prefer the first method,  which will do all this
            job for you!!!

            And, yes!! In both cases the handling routines are
            up to you!!!

@ENDNODE

@NODE Communicating_with_Editor "Communicating with Editor"

 *************************************************************************
 *THE FOLLOWING FUNCTIONS WORK ONLY IF EASINT IS LAUNCHED AS AN ACCESSORY*
 *************************************************************************

            EasInt offers the possibility of communicating with
            the AMOS PRO Editor,thus speeding up the code tran-
            splanting between EasInt and your programs.
            You can:

            1- Grab code from AMOS Editor
            2- Send code to AMOS Editor

            1- If you need to modify a Panel already defined in
               a program, this functions is for you!
               After importing the code you'll be able to modi-
               fy it as you want,  just like a brand-new EasInt
               Panel.

            2- This function allows you to insert your interfa-
               ce code directly in the source currently displa-
               yed in the active AMOS Editor window,without ha-
               ving to save it and then @{"Merge the ASCII file" Link Using_the_Panels_in_your_programs}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Testing_your_Panel "Testing your Panel"

            This function is  fundamental while creating a Pa-
            nel.  After  picking the Panel/Test Current  item,
            the Panel starts working, so that you can test any
            of its buttons and active zones: the position(sta-
            tus ) of the zone just tested  will be reported on
            EasInt's messages' panel; in this way, you'll have
            a good preview of how the Panel  will work in your
            programs.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Editing_your_Panel "Editing your Panel by hand"

            -------------------------------------------------
            ATTENTION:this function comes handy only when one
                      needs to use commands  NOT supported by
                      EasInt (why? @{"Here's the answer" Link Foreword}) and/or
                      create very complex Panels
            -------------------------------------------------

            When this function is called, a complete text ed
            (with its pull-down menus) will be opened.
            From that point on,anything can be typed straight
            in the Panel code.If you make a mistake, the code
            will be restored to its previous form.

            Normally, you won't need to program directly your
            Panel.

            NOTE: I advice you to save the Panel before ente-
                  ring this editor,  because it could go into
                  an infinite loop while trying to  debug the
                  code being edited. Sorry.... this is one of
                  those sh***y @{" BUGS " Link MajorBugs} I was talking about in
                  that sad @{" FOREWORD " Link Foreword}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE HELP "HELP"

            By selecting the EasInt/Help menu item you'll rece-
            ive some information about any option of the menu :
            that is why this guide is not very detailed, consi-
            dering also that EasInt is (as I believe) very easy
            to use.
            Once you have activated the Help function, just se-
            lect any option from the menu, and a brief explana-
            tion will be immediately given to you.
            Note that there is a @{"little problem" Link MinorFlaws} when using the
            shortcuts.

@ENDNODE

